9.Given the root of a binary tree and an integer targetSum, return the number of paths where the sum of the values along the path equals targetSum.
The path does not need to start or end at the root or a leaf, but it must go downwards (i.e., traveling only from parent nodes to child nodes).
 Platform : LeetCode
        SOURCE CODE :/**
 * Definition for a binary tree node.
 * public class TreeNode {
 *     int val;
 *     TreeNode left;
 *     TreeNode right;
 *     TreeNode() {}
 *     TreeNode(int val) { this.val = val; }
 *     TreeNode(int val, TreeNode left, TreeNode right) {
 *         this.val = val;
 *         this.left = left;
 *         this.right = right;
 *     }
 * }
 */
class Solution {

    public int pathSum(TreeNode root, int targetSum) {
        if (root == null)
            return 0;

        return count(root, targetSum)
                + pathSum(root.left, targetSum)
                + pathSum(root.right, targetSum);
    }

    private int count(TreeNode root, long target) {
        if (root == null)
            return 0;

        int ans = 0;

        if (root.val == target)
            ans++;

        ans += count(root.left, target - root.val);
        ans += count(root.right, target - root.val);

        return ans;
    }
}
    Link : https://leetcode.com/problems/path-sum-iii/?envType=study-plan-v2&envId=leetcode-75
    10.Two strings are considered close if you can attain one from the other using the following operations:

Operation 1: Swap any two existing characters.
For example, abcde -> aecdb
Operation 2: Transform every occurrence of one existing character into another existing character, and do the same with the other character.
For example, aacabb -> bbcbaa (all a's turn into b's, and all b's turn into a's)
 Platform : LeetCode
        SOURCE CODE : class Solution {
    public boolean closeStrings(String word1, String word2) {
        if (word1.length() != word2.length())
            return false;

        int[] f1 = new int[26];
        int[] f2 = new int[26];

        for (char c : word1.toCharArray())
            f1[c - 'a']++;

        for (char c : word2.toCharArray())
            f2[c - 'a']++;

        for (int i = 0; i < 26; i++) {
            if ((f1[i] == 0) != (f2[i] == 0))
                return false;
        }

        Arrays.sort(f1);
        Arrays.sort(f2);

        return Arrays.equals(f1, f2);
    }
}
    Link : https://leetcode.com/problems/determine-if-two-strings-are-close/?envType=study-plan-v2&envId=leetcode-75